<h2>HVAC Systems in South Carolina</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>South Carolina's humid subtropical climate creates specific HVAC requirements that differ significantly from other regions of the United States. The state experiences long, hot summers with high humidity levels often exceeding 70%, requiring air conditioning systems to work continuously from May through September. Average summer temperatures range from 85-95¬∞F, with heat index values frequently reaching over 100¬∞F. This extended cooling season means that air conditioning accounts for 50-70% of annual electricity consumption in most South Carolina homes, making efficient cooling systems essential for managing energy costs.</p>

<p>Winter heating requirements in South Carolina are generally modest, with average winter temperatures ranging from 40-60¬∞F. Most areas experience fewer than 3,000 heating degree days annually, significantly lower than northern states. However, occasional cold snaps can bring temperatures into the 20s, requiring reliable backup heating. Heat pump systems are ideal for South Carolina's climate because they provide efficient cooling during the long summer months and adequate heating during mild winters. For optimal performance, HVAC systems should have SEER ratings of at least 16, with high-efficiency units rated at 18-22 SEER providing the best long-term value in the state's climate.</p>

<p>Humidity control is equally important as temperature control in South Carolina. HVAC systems must be properly sized and equipped with adequate dehumidification capabilities to maintain indoor humidity levels between 40-50%. Oversized systems that cycle on and off frequently often fail to adequately remove humidity, leading to comfort issues and potential mold problems. Variable-speed air handlers and two-stage compressors help maintain consistent temperature and humidity levels while operating more efficiently than single-stage systems.</p>

