<h2>South Carolina Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>South Carolina offers one of the most generous solar incentive programs in the Southeast, making solar installations particularly attractive for homeowners and businesses. The state provides multiple layers of financial incentives that can significantly reduce the upfront cost of solar panel installations and improve return on investment timelines.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> The federal government provides a 30% tax credit for solar panel installations completed through 2032. This credit applies to the total cost of the solar system, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work. For a \$20,000 solar installation, homeowners can claim a \$6,000 federal tax credit. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds current tax liability, and there are no income restrictions or caps on the credit amount.</li>

<li><strong>South Carolina State Tax Credit:</strong> South Carolina offers an additional 25% state tax credit for solar installations, capped at \$5,250 per system or \$17,500 for three or more systems. This credit is claimed on South Carolina state income tax returns and can be carried forward for up to 10 years if it exceeds annual tax liability. Combined with the federal credit, homeowners can reduce their solar installation costs by up to 55%.</li>

<li><strong>Duke Energy Solar Rebate Program:</strong> Duke Energy Carolina and Duke Energy Progress offer rebates for residential solar installations within their service territories. The current rebate is \$0.60 per watt for systems up to 10kW, providing up to \$6,000 for a maximum-sized residential system. Rebate funds are limited and distributed on a first-come, first-served basis, making early application essential.</li>

<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Solar installations are exempt from property tax assessments in South Carolina, meaning that the added value of a solar system won't increase property taxes. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial installations and remains in effect for the life of the solar system.</li>

<li><strong>Net Metering:</strong> South Carolina requires utilities to offer net metering for solar customers, allowing excess solar production to be fed back into the grid for credit against future electricity consumption. Net metering credits are applied at the full retail rate, providing maximum value for solar production that exceeds household consumption.</li>

<li><strong>Local Utility Programs:</strong> Many municipal utilities and electric cooperatives throughout South Carolina offer additional rebates and incentive programs. For example, Santee Cooper offers rebates for energy-efficient HVAC systems, while several municipal utilities provide solar rebates that can be combined with state and federal incentives.</li>
</ul>

